# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: content-negotiation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] In computing, **content negotiation** refers to mechanisms defined as a part of HTTP that make it possible to serve different versions of a document (or more generally, representations of a resource) at the same URI, so that user agents can specify which version fits their capabilities the best.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] One classical use of this mechanism is to serve an image in GIF or PNG format, so that a browser that cannot display PNG images (e.g.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] MS Internet Explorer 4) will be served the GIF version.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] A resource may be available in several different representations; for example, it might be available in different languages or different media types.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] One way of selecting the most appropriate choice is to give the user an index page and let them select the most appropriate choice; however it is often possible to automate the choice based on some selection criteria.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] HTTP provides for several different content negotiation mechanisms including: server-driven (or proactive), agent-driven (or reactive), transparent, and/or hybrid combinations thereof.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Server-driven or proactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms on the server which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on user agent-provided acceptance criteria.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the user agent informs the server what media types or other aspects of content presentation it understands with ratings of how well it understands them.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] More precisely, the user agent provides HTTP headers that lists acceptable aspects of the resource and quality factors for them.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] The server is then able to supply the version of the resource that best fits the user agent's needs.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Where the 'q' - quality - factor for German is higher than that for English.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Multiple HTTP headers are often supplied together for content format or, specifically media type, language and a few other aspects of a resource.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] In addition to the commonly used `Accept` header for Media Type, the `Accept-Language` header for language negotiation, RFC 7231 also describes `Accept-Charset` & `Accept-Encodings` for character encodings and content codings (compression) respectively.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Neither RFC 7231 nor the more recent related specifications such as *Content Negotiation by Profile* specify how to resolve trade-offs in cases where different headers specify conflicting requirements, such as, in the above example, choosing between an HTML page in English and a GIF image in German.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Agent-driven or reactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms in the user-agent which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on a server provided list of representations and metadata about them.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the server informs the user-agent which representations it has available as well as any metadata it has about each representation (e.g., content-type, quality, language, etc.).
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] The user-agent then resubmits the request to a specific URL for the chosen representation.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] This can be automatically chosen by the user-agent or the user-agent can present the user with the choices and the user can directly choose such.
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] More precisely, the server responds with either 300 Multiple Choices or 406 Not Acceptable (when server-driven, user-agent acceptance criteria are provided but the server cannot automatically make a selection).
[src:content-negotiation/content-negotiation] Unfortunately HTTP leaves the format of the list of representations and metadata along with selection mechanisms unspecified.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] include the representation data in the body.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The following is a request with no body.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:content-negotiation/http-header] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] In information and communications technology, a **media type**, **content type** or **MIME type** is a two-part identifier for file formats and content formats.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Their purpose is comparable to filename extensions and uniform type identifiers, in that they identify the intended data format.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] They are mainly used by technologies underpinning the Internet, and also used on Linux desktop systems.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) is the official authority for the standardization and publication of these classifications.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Media types are also used by other internet protocols such as HTTP, document file formats such as HTML, and the XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments, for similar purposes.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Different internet standards or web standards bodies differ on the preferred term for this type of identifier.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The IANA and IETF use the term "media type", and consider the term "MIME type" to be obsolete, since media types have become used in contexts unrelated to email, such as HTTP.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] By contrast, the WHATWG continues to use the term "MIME type" and discourages use of the term "media type" as ambiguous, since it is used with a different meaning in connection with the CSS `@media` feature.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The HTTP response header for providing the media type is `Content-Type`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The W3C has used `ContentType` as an XML data-type name for a media type.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments continue to use the term "MIME type".
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] A media type consists of a *type* and a *subtype*, which is further structured into a *tree*.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] As an example, an HTML file might be designated `text/html; charset=UTF-8`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] In this example, `text` is the type, `html` is the subtype, and `charset=UTF-8` is an optional parameter indicating the character encoding.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Types, subtypes, and parameter names are case-insensitive.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Parameter values are usually case-sensitive, but may be interpreted in a case-insensitive fashion depending on the intended use.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The "type" part defines the broad use of the media type.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] As of November 1996, the registered types were `application`, `audio`,`image`, `message`, `multipart`, `text` and `video`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] By July 2024, the registered types included the foregoing, plus `font`, `example`, `model`, and `haptics`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] An unofficial top-level type in common use is `chemical`, used for chemical file formats.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] A subtype typically consists of a media format, but it may or must also contain other content, such as a tree prefix, producer, product or suffix, according to the different rules in registration trees.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] All media types should be registered using the IANA registration procedures.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] For the efficiency and flexibility of the media type registration process, different structures of subtypes can be registered in registration trees that are distinguished by the use of tree prefixes.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Currently, the following trees are created: standard (no prefix), vendor (`vnd.` prefix), personal or vanity (`prs.` prefix), unregistered (`x.` prefix).
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] These registration trees were first defined in November 1996 (obsoleted RFC 2048 - currently RFC 6838).
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] New registration trees may be created by IETF Standards Action for external registration and management by well-known permanent organizations (e.g. scientific societies).
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The standards tree does not use any tree prefix.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Examples are `text/javascript`, `image/png`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Registrations in the standards tree must be either associated with IETF specifications approved directly by the IESG, or registered by an IANA recognized standards-related organization.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The vendor tree includes media types associated with publicly available products.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Examples are: `application/vnd.ms-excel`, `application/vnd.oasis.opendocument.text`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The terms "vendor" and "producer" are considered equivalent in the context.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Industry consortia as well as non-commercial entities can register media types in the vendor tree.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] A registration in the vendor tree may be created by anyone who needs to interchange files associated with some software product or set of products.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] However, the registration belongs to the vendor or organization producing the software that employs the type being registered, and that vendor or organization can at any time elect to assert ownership of a registration done by a third party.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The personal or vanity tree includes media types associated with non publicly available products or experimental media types.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Examples are `audio/prs.sid`, `image/prs.btif`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The unregistered tree includes media types intended exclusively for use in private environments and only with the active agreement of the parties exchanging them.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Examples are `application/x.foo`, `video/x.bar`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Media types in this tree cannot be registered.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] This type was originally defined in RFC 1590 (published in September 1993) using the `x-` or `X-` prefix.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] RFC 2048 (published in November 1996) introduced the `x.` prefix, but discouraged use of the unregistered tree, as new personal and vendor trees with relaxed registration requirements are now available.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The current RFC 6838 (published in January 2013) maintains the same recommendation, but subtypes prefixed with `x-` or `X-` are no longer considered to be members of this tree.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Media types that have been widely deployed (with a subtype prefixed with `x-` or `X-`) without being registered, should be, if possible, re-registered with a proper prefixed subtype.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] If this is not possible, the media type can, after an approval by both the media types reviewer and the IESG, be registered in the standards tree with its unprefixed subtype.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is an example of a widely deployed type that ended up registered with the `x-` prefix.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Suffix is an augmentation to the media type definition to additionally specify the underlying structure of that media type, allowing for generic processing based on that structure and independent of the exact type's particular semantics.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Media types that make use of a named structured syntax should use the appropriate IANA registered `"+"suffix` for that structured syntax when they are registered.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Unregistered suffixes should not be used (since January 2013).
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Structured syntax suffix registration procedures are defined in RFC 6838.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The +xml suffix has been defined since January 2001 (RFC 3023), and was formally included in the initial contents of the Structured Syntax Suffix Registry along with `+json`, `+ber`, `+der`, `+fastinfoset`, `+wbxml`, and `+zip` in January 2013 (RFC 6839).
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Subsequent additions include `+gzip`, `+cbor`, `+json-seq`, and `+cbor-seq`.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Mailcap (derived from the phrase "mail capability") is a type of meta file used to configure how MIME-aware applications such as mail clients and web browsers render files of different MIME-types.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] The mailcap format is defined by RFC 1524 "A User Agent Configuration Mechanism for Multimedia Mail Format Information" but is not defined as an Internet standard.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Lines can be comments starting with the # character, or a mime-type followed by how to handle that mime type.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] An associated file is the **mime.types** file, which associates filename extensions with a *MIME type*.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] If the MIME type is properly set, this is unnecessary, but MIME types may be incorrectly set, or set to a generic type such as `application/octet-stream`, and **mime.types** allows one to fall back on the extension in these cases.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] Similarly, since many file systems do not store MIME type information, but instead rely on the filename extension, a mime.types file is frequently used by web servers to determine MIME type.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] When *viewing* a file, these two work together as follows: **`mime.types`** associates an extension with a MIME type, while `mailcap` associates a MIME type with a program.
[src:content-negotiation/media-type] In UNIX-type systems, the mime.types file is usually located at `/etc/**mime.types**` and/or `$HOME/**.mime.types**` and the format is simply that each line is a space-delimited list of a MIME type, followed by zero or more extensions.
